<font color="#FF0000">ABANDONMENT</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec  7  0:22:17 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The &quot;contrary&quot; has reminded me of the ills of abandonment.  Certainly, Viet Nam vets are familiar with having been abandoned.  Not like the counterfiet, humorous war story conjured up by the idiot above, but more subtle...of course there were instances where men were left behind...presumed dead or for the practical necessity to save the rest!  Always, the one left behind who survived felt differently. Some were forgiving and understood... others where/are angry, but all must feel a deep rooted sense of pain...if ever left behind.  Fortunately, that only happened to a few combatants.  What did happen to the masses of returning vets is a more far reaching and thorough type of abandonment and rejection.  The example given by our moronic &quot;contrary&quot; above clearly illustrates the need for America to pay homeage to all its veterans in all wars and conflicts.  Acceptance into a fraternity of brothers who share common war experiences is a good beginning to thwart the old trauma of being rejected.<br><br>
Captain Edward Ramon - RVN '66'67 '69
